---
import ServiceLayout from '../../layouts/ServiceLayout.astro';
import { SITE_TITLE } from '../../consts';
---

<ServiceLayout
	title={`Nix Systems Design | ${SITE_TITLE}`}
	description="Declarative, reproducible infrastructure. Your systems become code—immutable, testable, perfectly reproducible."
>
	<div class="header-section">
		<div class="logo-header">
			<img src="/logos/nix-logo.svg" alt="NixOS" width="64" height="64" />
		</div>
		<h1>Nix Systems Design</h1>
	</div>
	<p class="intro">
		Declarative, reproducible infrastructure. Your systems become code—immutable, testable, perfectly reproducible.
	</p>

	<section class="overview">
		<h2>What This Offers</h2>
		<p>
			Nix transforms how you manage systems and development environments. Instead of imperatively
			installing packages and hoping they work together, you declare what you want—and Nix ensures
			you get exactly that, every time, on every machine.
		</p>
		<p>
			From developer workstations to production servers, Nix provides atomic upgrades, instant
			rollbacks, and the confidence that your infrastructure is reproducible.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="capabilities">
		<h2>Capabilities</h2>
		<div class="grid">
			<div class="capability">
				<h3>NixOS Infrastructure</h3>
				<p>
					Fully declarative server and workstation deployments. Atomic upgrades, instant rollbacks,
					and identical environments across dev and production.
				</p>
			</div>
			<div class="capability">
				<h3>Flakes & Packages</h3>
				<p>
					Custom package repositories, development shells with pinned dependencies, and reproducible
					build pipelines. Lock your dependencies and never worry about "works on my machine."
				</p>
			</div>
			<div class="capability">
				<h3>Remote Deployment</h3>
				<p>
					nixos-rebuild deploy, colmena, and disko for bare-metal provisioning. Automated system
					provisioning at scale with declarative disk layouts.
				</p>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section class="ideal-for">
		<h2>Ideal For</h2>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Developer Workstations:</strong> Reproducible dev environments with exact dependency versions</li>
			<li><strong>Home Servers:</strong> Declarative configuration for personal infrastructure</li>
			<li><strong>Development Shells:</strong> Project-specific environments without polluting your system</li>
			<li><strong>Configuration Management:</strong> Dotfiles and system settings as code, version-controlled</li>
			<li><strong>Home Labs:</strong> Experimental setups with easy rollback when things break</li>
		</ul>
	</section>

	<section class="example">
		<h2>Philosophy</h2>
		<p>
			Nix treats your system configuration as a pure function: given the same inputs (your configuration),
			you always get the same output (your system state). This eliminates configuration drift, dependency
			hell, and the fear of system updates.
		</p>
		<p>
			Break something? Roll back to the previous generation. Want to test a new setup? Build it in parallel
			without touching your working system. Need to replicate your environment on a new machine? Just copy
			your config and rebuild.
		</p>
	</section>
</ServiceLayout>

<style>
	/* Dark is default (no class) — boost logo brightness on dark bg */
	:root:not(.light) .logo-header img {
		filter: brightness(1.2);
	}
</style>
